ersonal experiences of the emigrants aboard these vessels offer us a much more complex understanding of this pivotal moment in modern history. Based on archival research on three continents and written in clear, crisp prose, The Coffin Ship analyzes the emigrants’ own letters and diaries to unpack the dynamic social networks that the Irish built while voyaging overseas. At every step of the journey—including the treacherous weeks at sea—these migrants created new threads in the worldwide web of the Irish diaspora.Colored by the long-lost voices of the emigrants themselves, this is an original portrait of an overlooked aspect of the migration process that left an undeniable mark on their new lives overseas. An indispensable read, The Coffin Ship makes an ambitious argument for placing the sailing ship alongside the tenement and the factory floor as a central, dynamic element of migration history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aImmigrantsvCorrespondence. 0aImmigrantsxHistoryy19th century. 0aIrishzForeign countriesxHistoryy19th century. 0aOcean travelxHistoryy19th century. 0aPassenger shipszGreat BritainxHistoryy19th century. 0aSeafaring life. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Ireland.2bisacsh  aAmerican History.  aAssisted Migration.  aBlack ‘47.  aBurials.  aCanals.  aCharity.  aCholera.  aCleanliness.  aClothing.  aCommunication.  aCommunity.  aConvict Transportation.  aConvicts.  aDelayed Departures.  aDiscipline.  aDisembarkation.  aEmbarkation.  aEmigrant Mortality Rates.  aEmigrant Relief.  aFamily.  aFunerals.  aGender.  aHierarchy.  aHousing.  aImmigration.  aLandlords.  aLiverpool.  aMaritime History.  aMourning.  aPopular Press.  aPower.  aRailroads.  aRemittances.  aResistance.  aSea Stores.  aSeas and Oceans.  aSocial Class.